  "What is sonar?": "",
  "An instrument for collecting ocean sediment samples": "",
  "A device that measures water temperature": "",
  "A technology that uses sound waves to measure ocean depth and map the seafloor by timing echoes": "",
  "A type of underwater camera": "",
  "Sonar (Sound Navigation and Ranging) sends sound pulses toward the ocean floor and measures the time for the echo to return, allowing calculation of depth and mapping of features.": "",
  "What is seafloor spreading?": "",
  "The expansion of the ocean due to sea level rise": "",
  "The process by which new oceanic crust forms at mid-ocean ridges as tectonic plates move apart and magma rises to fill the gap": "",
  "The spreading of pollution across the ocean floor": "",
  "Sediment being deposited on the ocean floor": "",
  "Seafloor spreading creates new oceanic crust at mid-ocean ridges where plates diverge, with the youngest rocks found at the ridge crest and progressively older rocks further away.": "",
  "A research vessel uses sonar to map a section of the Atlantic Ocean floor and discovers the ocean crust is youngest at the Mid-Atlantic Ridge and gets progressively older moving toward the continents on either side. What does this age pattern tell us about how the Atlantic Ocean formed?": "",
  "The Atlantic is slowly growing wider through seafloor spreading at the Mid-Atlantic Ridge, with new crust continuously forming at the ridge and pushing older crust outward": "",
  "The entire Atlantic Ocean basin formed instantaneously during a single catastrophic geological event long ago": "",
  "Surface erosion from ocean currents removed older material at the ridge, making those rocks appear younger": "",
  "The oldest oceanic crust sank toward the center of the basin while newer lighter material stayed at the edges": "",
  "The symmetrical age pattern confirms seafloor spreading: new crust forms at the ridge and moves outward, so the Atlantic has been widening at about 2.5 cm/year as North America and Europe separate.": "",
  "Scientists discover a thriving community of giant tube worms, clams, and bacteria near a hydrothermal vent on the ocean floor at 2,500 meters depth where no sunlight penetrates. How can such abundant life exist without sunlight?": "",
  "The hot water from vents provides heat energy for photosynthesis": "",
  "Chemosynthetic bacteria at the vents convert hydrogen sulfide and other chemicals into energy, forming the base of the food web without any sunlight": "",
  "Food particles from the surface sink down to feed them": "",
  "The organisms are photosynthetic and use bioluminescence": "",
  "Hydrothermal vent ecosystems are powered by chemosynthesis, where bacteria use energy from chemical reactions (hydrogen sulfide) rather than sunlight to produce organic compounds.": "",
