  "Canyon walls are made of a material that interferes with cable signals": "",
  "Submarine canyons are too shallow for cables": "",
  "Turbidity currents are fast-moving underwater sediment flows that can reach speeds of 70 km/h, powerful enough to snap submarine cables, as documented in the 1929 Grand Banks event.": "",
  "A marine geologist notices that a chain of seamounts in the Pacific Ocean gets progressively older as you move northwest from Hawaii. The youngest seamount is still an active volcano. What geological process explains this pattern?": "",
  "A series of volcanic eruptions along a plate boundary": "",
  "A stationary hot spot in the mantle creates volcanoes as the Pacific Plate moves northwest over it, producing a chain of progressively older seamounts": "",
  "The seamounts are all the same age but at different depths": "",
  "Underwater landslides created the seamount chain": "",
  "The Hawaiian-Emperor seamount chain formed as the Pacific Plate moved northwest over a fixed mantle hot spot, creating a trail of volcanic islands and seamounts that get older with distance.": "",
  "A deep-sea mining company proposes extracting mineral-rich deposits from hydrothermal vents on the ocean floor. Environmental scientists raise concerns. What unique ecosystems would be threatened by deep-sea mining at vent sites?": "",
  "Shallow-water coral reef systems that depend on sunlight for photosynthesis by their symbiotic algae partners": "",
  "Chemosynthesis-based communities with unique species like tube worms and vent shrimp found nowhere else, which are extremely slow to recover from disturbance": "",
  "Dense underwater kelp forest ecosystems that grow along the mid-ocean ridge using nutrients from vent water": "",
  "No significant biological ecosystems exist at hydrothermal vent depths because conditions are too extreme": "",
  "Hydrothermal vent ecosystems host unique species found nowhere else on Earth, including giant tube worms and specialized shrimp, and these slow-growing communities would take decades to recover from mining.": "",
  "Despite covering over 70% of Earth's surface, less than 25% of the ocean floor has been mapped in detail. A student asks why mapping the ocean floor is harder than mapping land or even other planets. What makes ocean floor mapping so challenging?": "",
  "The ocean floor has essentially no interesting or distinctive geological features that would justify mapping efforts": "",
  "The ocean floor changes shape too rapidly due to constant volcanic activity for any map to remain accurate": "",
  "Satellite remote sensing can easily map the ocean floor with high resolution but no government has funded it": "",
  "Light and electromagnetic signals like radar cannot penetrate deep water, so ships must use sonar which covers small areas slowly, and the vast ocean size makes comprehensive mapping extremely time-consuming": "",
  "Unlike land surfaces that can be mapped by satellite radar, ocean mapping requires sonar-equipped ships because electromagnetic signals are absorbed by water, making coverage slow and expensive.": "",
  "A fishing community on the west coast of South America is located near the Peru-Chile Trench. They experience frequent earthquakes and tsunamis. Why is their location especially prone to these natural hazards?": "",
  "The trench creates unusually strong tidal forces that amplify wave energy and produce dangerous coastal surges": "",
  "The Peru-Chile Trench is a subduction zone where the Nazca Plate dives beneath the South American Plate, generating powerful earthquakes that can trigger tsunamis": "",
  "The extreme depth of the trench water column amplifies incoming wave energy and directs it toward the coastline": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions from magma chambers directly beneath the trench floor generate most of the tsunamis in the area": "",
  "Ocean trenches are subduction zones where plates converge, generating some of the world's most powerful earthquakes as stored stress is released, which can displace water and create tsunamis.": "",
  "A marine biologist discovers that the continental shelf, which makes up only about 8% of the ocean floor area, supports a disproportionately large amount of marine life. Why is the continental shelf so biologically productive compared to the deep ocean?": "",
  "Shallow water allows sunlight to penetrate to the bottom, rivers deliver nutrients, and diverse habitats support abundant food webs": "",
  "The water on continental shelves is warmer": "",
  "The deep ocean has no nutrients for life": "",
  "Continental shelves have stronger currents that bring food": "",
  "Continental shelves are productive because sunlight reaches the bottom for photosynthesis, river runoff delivers nutrients, and varied habitats (reefs, seagrass beds, sandy bottoms) support diverse ecosystems.": "",
  "Scientists find that the rocks on either side of the Mid-Atlantic Ridge are mirror images of each other, with matching magnetic stripe patterns. What does this symmetrical pattern of magnetic reversals tell us about the Earth and the ocean floor?": "",
  "As new crust forms at the ridge, iron minerals align with Earth's current magnetic field and are preserved, so matching stripes on both sides confirm that new rock is created and pushed outward symmetrically": "",
